1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
Hey there coders! Today we're exploring Python variables. Think of variables as containers for storing data values.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:15,000
In Python, creating a variable is as simple as assigning a value to it.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:27,000
Here's an example. In this code, X is a variable that holds the number 5, which is an integer, and Y is a variable that holds the text John, which is a string.

4
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Python doesn't need a special command to declare a variable. It's created the moment you assign it a value.

5
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Variables in Python are dynamic. They don't need to be of a specific type, and can change type after being set.

6
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Here, X starts as an integer with the value 4, then changes to a string with the value Sally.

7
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:59,000
If you want to specify the data type of a variable, you can use casting.

8
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:05,000
This way, you can control the data type of your variables.

9
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Want to know the type of a variable? Use the type function.

10
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Here, type X returns class STR, type Y returns class int, and type Z returns class float.

11
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:24,000
In Python, strings can be declared with either single or double quotes.

12
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Both lines do the same thing. It's up to you which style you prefer.

13
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:33,000
Remember, variable names in Python are case sensitive.

14
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:37,000
That means lowercase A and uppercase A are different variables.

15
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:43,000
In this case, lowercase A holds the integer 4, and uppercase A holds the string Sally.

16
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:46,000
One doesn't overwrite the other.

17
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:50,000
And that's a wrap on Python variables.

18
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:54,000
Keep practicing, and you'll be a Python pro in no time.

19
